column48:
1. School choice needs to have a lot more discretion as to how it is distributed. Funds should be reserved for families who are in underserved communities. School choice dollars should not replace funding to public schools. I would like to see more effort put toward building excellent public schools with vouchers for those families who need assistance in getting their children to school at all, such as a family with a special needs child who wants to attend a school devoted to special needs children.
2. I don't think continuing to raise the age of full retirement is the correct solution for Social Security. People should not have to work until they are physically debilitated before they can qualify to receive full benefits - that is completely wrong! Full benefits at the age of 65 allows workers to enjoy the fruits of their many years of labor while they might still be relatively able-bodied. The people of the American workforce DESERVE this! I'm sure there are many other ways that social security payouts can be managed and costs controlled. One ovious way to handle SS funds is to cap how much of it the government can borrow, so that there are always the funds necessary to pay back to workers when they decide to retire. It is the same concept as balancing a checkbook. If I spent $100 at the grocery store, I debit $100 from my balance and consider it gone. If I try to spend money based on how much I think might be in my account before a debit has completed processing - that is how I end up in trouble. Likewise, the government needs to stop taking from Social Security based on guesstimating when people will decide to draw on their savings - YES! THEIR SAVINGS!! It is our money to take back when we choose. The government needs to stop taking from it, and stop dangling the carrot further and further away, and finding ways to withhold worker's earnings from them. PERIOD.

column48:
The education proposals need serious work, as they are doubling down on "No Excuses"-style education reforms that focus on school and teacher accountability; this just pulls from a familiar strategy employed during NCLB and Race to the Top, which we know does not work.  The most significant problems in education are caused by societal problems; primarily, economic issues are to blame, such as our high level of childhood poverty. Structural changes to housing, wages, and healthcare will actually improve educational outcomes. See the research of Jean Anyon and David Berliner for more information. 

In terms of healthcare, we must move to a Medicaid-for-all public system. The rest of the world has shown us the way; we just need to follow. A related point: you'd be wise to focus more on tackling campaign finance reform, lobbying, and the unrestrained influence of corporations on our elected officials. ALL of our problems are related to this, as entrenched interests want to halt progress because it would reduce their access, profit, and power.

column48:
Require and provide all voters EASY access to politician's voting records as well as statements they have made publicly.
Give all political candidates a national day of debate and a NO MONEY to spend on their campaign. Remove the ability for corporations and the wealthy to buy politicians and government.
Hold politicians accountable for their "promises".
Bills should only contain one issue and be easily understood by politicians and their constituents. 
Presidents should not be above the law but instead should be held more accountable since they should be setting examples of upholding our laws.
Age limits for public office should be retirement age used for Social Security.
Cognitive tests for President's should be given and broadcasted publicly.
For at least a decade, pay people to vote. 
Have a national holiday for Presidential elections. Have early and mail in voting for all elections.
Make the Supreme Court contain 3 Conservatives, 3 Moderates, 3 Liberals. Set a retirement age, same as Social Security for a Justice to leave the Court.
Get rid of political parties. We should be voting for our choice of best candidate, not feel duty bound to a political party.
Until there are no more political parties, we voters should be able to vote for any candidate without declaring a Party on our Voter Registrations.
Take away politician's Social media accounts.
Prevent politicians and their immediate family members from trading in the Stock Market.
Enforce the Emoluments Clause. No President should be gaining wealth on the backs of the taxpayers.
Tax all Wall Street transactions at least 1 cent each, this alone would pay off our current deficit. 
All World Nations should wipe away debts to each other.
Our military in other countries shoul be helping to provide clean drinking water and helping to build up relations with other nations.
A President and other political office holders should never be allowed to place family members into government positions.
A President should be given a certain number of hours for leisure time and not be allowed to travel thousands of miles for that leisure.
All government positions for those who keep the Executive Branch accountable to our Constitution should be voting for by the people of this nation.

For example, a package could prioritize campaign finance reform to reduce the influence of corporate and special interests, as well as a comprehensive overhaul of the electoral system, such as ranked-choice voting, to encourage more moderate candidates and break the two-party gridlock. Additionally, focusing on issues like affordable healthcare and education could unite people, as these are problems many Americans face daily. By framing these proposals not as partisan victories but as solutions for the common good, we can hopefully build the broad support needed to overcome congressional inertia and move our country forward.
